{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QuxU5PZgxWWLauwWYt6JJa","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the problem clearly. The setup job:\n\n1. Created the `/app` vhost ✓\n2. Created the `app-user` user ✓\n3. Set permissions for `app-user` on `/app` vhost with `configure:\"\"` (empty - no configure permissions!), `write:\".*\"`, `read:\".*\"` ✓ but wait...\n\nThe issue is the `configure` permission. The app-producer is trying to **declare** (create) a queue, which requires **configure** permissions. But the setup set `configure` to `\"\"` (empty string = no configure permissions).\n4. There's also a policy forcing all queues to be quorum type across both vhosts, but the producer is attempting to declare a classic queue instead, which conflicts with that policy.\n\nSo I'm looking at two distinct issues: the `app-user` lacks configure permissions entirely, preventing queue declaration, and the `force-quorum` policy will override any attempt to create a classic queue. I need to either grant configure permissions and remove the policy constraint, or adjust the policy to allow classic queues alongside quorum ones. The permissions issue is clear—the empty configure permission string blocks queue declaration entirely. I need to create a temporary pod that uses the RabbitMQ management API to grant proper configure permissions to the app-user on the /app vhost and remove the force-quorum policy that's conflicting with the classic queue declaration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1633,"cache_read_input_tokens":35385,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1633},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a1f5e8a-4307-43cd-a3d6-52110567492e",